The Grasshopper Years of Latin America
The bad news continues to accumulate these days in Latin America.
Economic conditions are deteriorating almost everywhere, social cohesion is unraveling, and political instability is growing.
It is hardly surprising since the majority of Latin American countries have spent the last twenty years going nowhere.
Capital has been sold and national debts have been increased immeasurably, but nothing durable and beneficial has been achieved.
These years have really been eaten away by locusts.
Over the last 20 years, the annual growth rate of GDP per capita in Latin America has reached an average of 0.35%.
At this rate, an economy would take 200 years to double.
In Asia, the standard of living doubles every decade.
With such anemic growth, how can Latin America hope to compete in global trade apart from through a timid rise in wages?
Economic stagnation is the responsibility of bad government, not bad luck.
If Latin America does not change, it may start to look more and more like Africa - a region composed of weak states with large informal economies and widespread poverty.
Four factors have placed it on this path.
Firstly, in the rush to privatize, everything from public services to manufacturing industries has been auctioned off.
For a brief moment, capital sales helped balance national budgets and also provided resources to support consumption.
Finally, revenues from privatization have yielded little in terms of better infrastructure or more competitive exports.
Worse still, the sale of state assets was accompanied by massive external borrowing.
In some cases, notably in Argentina, the borrowing by national buyers exhausted all available credit lines.
Other countries have not fallen to the level of Argentina, but solvency represents a problem in almost all Latin American countries.
Secondly, since the reform did not bring prosperity, the region has become disillusioned.
The inflow of capital created a wealth effect, but only as long as they existed.
When the money stopped flowing, the wealth dried up.
No sensible politician would commit to another decade of structural reforms that would test the patience of average Latin Americans beyond the limits of electoral survival.
But without a greater number of deep reforms, too few prerequisites for economic growth will be met to attract investments, without which no growth is possible.
This development dilemma announces the third factor: incompetent policies.
The governments that operated along technocratic lines and viewed economic growth as a rising tide that lifts all boats have disappeared.
In Argentina, clumsy presidents succeed one another.
Institutions are being dismantled, property rights are being questioned, and a more random and corrupt redistribution effort is underway.
Peru and Venezuela have not much better chances; Brazil may soon follow the same path.
The popularity of Lula Ignacio da Silva and his team, who lead opinion polls in the period preceding the Brazilian presidential elections, indicates that a large part of the Latin American population is ready to reject traditional governments.
Lula and his party are so far from the dominant economic and political thinking that capital has already begun to flee - even though elections are only a few months away.
In Mexico, democratization has brought greater stability, but this could well turn out to be fleeting.
The peso is now excessively overvalued.
If the external balance deteriorates further, the economy risks landing hard.
As for all the good news about the emerging democracy in Mexico, its president is beginning to justify the fears that existed about it: no vision, no Congress, and no team knowing what it has to do.
The last factor concerns the desperately low savings rate that is endemic to the Americas.
In fact, this is the financial result economically speaking because where there is little savings, there is little investment - and little basis for accumulating capital and increasing productivity.
Venezuela now longs for the fat 1970s of OPEC -- to which it did not participate, having neglected to develop its oil industry.
The wealth of Argentina is now taking vacations in Miami, perhaps for good.
Brazil and Mexico constitute perfect examples of countries that have sold their assets and borrowed rather than saved.
The contrast with Asia is striking.
Take China, where savings and investment rates reach almost 40%, where the current account is in surplus and where there is no public debt.
Government institutions are in favor of the market and the population is well-educated, disciplined, and flexible in its learning.
The rewards for taking risks and initiative are immediate and strongly motivating.
One cannot deny that China remains a poor country.
Its GDP per capita is only half that of Brazil's.
But with a growth rate in China's coastal region of about 15% per year, who can seriously doubt that in the next 15 years, it will surpass Brazil?
In China, despite all the huge problems encountered, things continue to proceed correctly, first of all due to the massive inflow of foreign direct investments and the imminent benefits of joining the WTO.
In Latin America, things continue to fall apart: governments are backtracking on reforms and the economy is losing ground compared to the rest of the world.
Latin America was doing well when unregulated funds were flowing in, but those times are largely over.
We must therefore expect much worse economic, social, and political news in the years to come.
Demagogues such as Hugo Chavez in Venezuela or Carlos Menem -- an Argentine presidential candidate once again -- may seem like a bad joke, but anyone who cares about the destiny of Latin America should not laugh at them.
